Day1 Documentation

Internal Internship – Week 1 – Day 1
Student: Art Halili
Class: XI/3

1. Overview

On Day 1, the main focus was to set up the development environment, learn the basics of C programming, and understand how to use Git and GitHub for collaboration. This documentation explains the steps followed and the work completed.

2. C Compiler Installation

A C compiler was installed on the computer to allow writing and running C programs. After installation, the compiler was tested to ensure it works correctly.

Verification:
A simple program was compiled and executed successfully, confirming that the setup was correct.

3. Hello World Program

The first program created was a simple “Hello World” in C.

Purpose:
To test the compiler and understand the structure of a basic C program.

Key Concepts Learned:

Use of #include <stdio.h>
Structure of the main() function
Output using printf()
4. Student Profile Program

A second program was created to display a student profile.

Purpose:
To practice using variables and printing formatted output.

Concepts Used:

Variables (string and integer)
Data types (char, int)
Output formatting with printf()
5. Git and GitHub Workflow

Git and GitHub were used to manage the project and enable collaboration.

Steps Followed:

Repository was created
Repository was cloned locally
Personal branch was created
Files were added and committed
Changes were pushed to GitHub
6. Branch Rules
Each student worked in their own branch
No work was pushed to the main branch
Branch name followed the format: Name-Surname

This ensured safe and organized collaboration.

7. Project Structure

The following structure was created:

Day1/

hello_world.c
student_profile.c
Day1_Documentation.docx

All names were case-sensitive and followed exactly as required.

8. Git Commands Used
git clone – to download the repository
git branch – to create a personal branch
git switch – to move to the branch
git add – to stage files
git commit – to save changes
git push – to upload work
9. Conclusion

Day 1 was successfully completed. The environment was set up, basic programs were created, and GitHub workflow was understood. This provides a strong base for future internship tasks.
